{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G3 child-coverage audit — parent c81c plan-review fan-out epic; this child S4 (merge G3+G4 into one call per bin) reviewed WHOLE against the full sibling roster]\n\n4-bucket audit of the parent's acceptance/success criteria, mapping S4's contribution and cross-checking every absence against the roster (S1 0250, S2 c6e5, S3 ba7e, S5 1762, S6 da34):\n\n- \"materially lower token cost (cache reads non-zero) / completes in minutes\" (AC2 / Success) — PARTIALLY covered here: S4 halves container calls 2N->N, a direct token-and-call reduction (AC: \"container call count halves (2N -> N)\"). Wall-clock parallelization is delegated to sibling S3 (ba7e), the cache cost lever to S1 (0250). The 2N->N projection is grounded — S4's remediation correctly targets the live `container_floor_usd = len(container) * n_children * COST_AGENT_USD` at sizing.py:232. Covered across roster.\n- \"findings within offline-eval tolerance / no fidelity regression\" (AC4 / Success) — PARTIALLY covered here: S4 carries the MERGE-SPECIFIC fidelity obligation (\"offline eval shows no accuracy regression vs separate G3/G4 calls\" + \"S6 harness shows merged-call findings within tolerance\"), correctly gated on the S6 semantic harness (DEPENDS ON S6, declared via the da34->98c6 blocks link). The merge's distinct attribution risk (model-self-reported G3-vs-G4, validate-and-drop mirroring passes.py:222-224 — confirmed: the existing container path hardcodes `[cid]` at passes.py:277, which the merge necessarily replaces) is covered by S4's own ACs. Covered.\n- \"caching provider-safe: openai/gemini succeed unchanged\" (AC3) — STRUCTURAL w.r.t. S4 (no caching surface; owned by S1/S2). Covered by roster.\n- \"make lint + full suite pass\" (AC5) — per-child portion covered here (\"`make lint` + tests pass\").\n- \"caching across plan-review AND all workflow agent steps\" (Success) — outside S4 scope (S1 runner seam + S2 engine-wide). Covered by roster.\n- \"all six child stories (S1-S6) closed\" (AC1) — aggregate/structural; not a single-child mapping.\n\nANTI-FP cross-check on the one plausible absence: the per-child DEPTH / tail-child guardrail that batching introduces (the \"REQUIRED structured per-child output guardrail\" the epic meta-review flags as ESSENTIAL and \"must also apply to S4\") is a CONSISTENCY/completeness concern across S4/S5/S6, not an uncovered PARENT acceptance/success criterion — and the roster already carries it (S5 owns the guardrail, S6's eval is tasked to check tail-child recall). It is therefore not a G3 absence finding for this pairing.\n\nResult: G3 CLEAN — no findings. S4 is a coherent contributor to the coverage map; no parent acceptance/success criterion is left uncovered by the union of children, and S4 introduces no coverage gap that no sibling fills."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782578695880651001,"uuid":"02fef8ca-877c-4601-b8a1-803db5abb3e9"}